"adr-0018-thread-serialization": {
  storyboard: [
    "I was handed the persistence story when a customer reported their agent answering as if it had amnesia after a deploy. The thread had been written by version 1.2, the runtime was now 1.7, and our naive 'pickle the object graph' had broken on a class refactor. I knew that wouldn't survive multi-day [durable agent](#/concept/feature-durable-agents) sessions, cross-language interop, or any of the next ten releases.",
    "The forces I had to balance: cross-language parity (Python and .NET writing/reading the same wire format), polymorphic content (text, tool calls, approvals, structured outputs, custom items), forward compatibility (older runtime reading newer thread), and backward compatibility (newer runtime reading older thread). The pressure point was that on-disk format is the hardest thing to change after release — every active thread pins you.",
    "I framed the decision as **JSON, versioned, polymorphic via a discriminator field, additive-only schema evolution, ignored-unknown-fields semantics, preserve-on-write for round-trip safety**. Provider extensions ride in a typed extension bag. I rejected protobuf because the operational cost — schema registry, codegen pipelines per language — outweighed the wire-size win for thread sizes dominated by message text. I rejected free-form JSON because polymorphism without discriminators is unsolvable.",
    "What landed: threads written by 1.2 still load in 1.7; multi-day human-in-the-loop sessions survive deploys; cross-language agents (a .NET frontend, a Python backend) hand each other threads. What I'd still change: silent lossy round-trip is a CI property test today; I'd add a runtime canary that diffs reads/writes against recorded prod threads, because humans still get 'preserve unknowns on write' wrong."
  ],
  star: {
    situation: "Thread state had to survive multi-day human-in-the-loop, restartable durable agents, version upgrades, and cross-language interop. Naive serialisation strategies (pickle, free-form JSON) broke on every refactor or release.",
    task: "My job was to design a stable on-disk format that was forward- and backward-compatible by construction, additive-only within a major version, and round-trip-safe under unknown fields.",
    action: "I picked JSON with explicit version, polymorphic discriminator on every item, and preserve-on-write for unknown fields. Round-trip property tests gate every release. Major-version migrations get an explicit one-shot migration tool with a documented format diff. I refused protobuf because the operational cost outweighed the wire-size win on text-dominated threads.",
    result: "The framework ships threads that load across language and version boundaries. Long-lived sessions survive deploys; cross-language interop is real. Round-trip CI catches the silent-lossy-read class of bug; the runtime canary is the residual."
  },
  leadership: [
    { lp: "Insist on the Highest Standards", note: "Round-trip property tests gate every release, because 'preserve unknowns on write' is a discipline humans get wrong and the only honest way to enforce it is mechanically." },
    { lp: "Are Right, A Lot", note: "JSON over protobuf was the right call for text-dominated threads; the operational cost of schema registries would have outweighed the wire-size win. The trade is honest about the use case." },
    { lp: "Success and Scale Bring Broad Responsibility", note: "Multi-day durable sessions outlive deploys, releases, and team turnover — the on-disk format is effectively immutable, and we treat it as such." },
    { lp: "Frugality", note: "Provider extensions ride in a typed bag rather than forking the canonical schema, so we don't pay for an extension dialect we don't use." }
  ],
  elevatorPitch: "Agent threads have to survive multi-day waits, version upgrades, cross-language interop, and process restarts — and naive serialisation breaks on the first refactor. I picked JSON, versioned, polymorphic via a discriminator field, additive-only within a major version, with preserve-on-write for unknown fields so older runtimes don't lossy-write newer threads. Round-trip property tests gate every release because 'preserve unknowns' is a discipline humans get wrong. I rejected protobuf because the operational cost — schema registry, per-language codegen — outweighed the wire-size win for text-dominated threads. The win is that a thread written by 1.2 still loads in 1.7 and a .NET frontend can hand a Python backend a thread without re-encoding. The honest residual: I'd add a runtime canary that diffs reads/writes against recorded prod threads, because CI alone misses production drift."
},

